text: first step use package dataframe containing least taxid column containing NCBI format TaxIds. dataframe can also contain data might want visualise. can transform dataframe format suitable visualisation functions package build_Lifemap function. , get lifemap object takes form list containing following informations : df : containing augmented dataframe obtained first step. can visualise data lifemap() associated one following functions : lm_markers(), represent data circles. lm_branches(), represent data’s subtree. lm_discret(), represent discret data piecharts. one three function adds layer visualisation. layers combined + symbol. function also allow user represent data modifying characteristics representations ’ll see later examples. output shiny interface user can move zoom freely. Please note following examples done may 2023, try may values due database update
code: ##      taxid                            sci_name zoom        lat        lon ## 6  1003877                         Benincaseae   20  9.3045287  -7.026574 ## 7  1004254         Cyberlindnera subsufficiens   24  6.3209234 -10.574330 ## 8  1008252                             Melinae   25 -0.9759531 -12.991605 ## 9   100860                         Aphanomyces   17 -7.8909783 -12.002886 ## 10  100903 Fusarium oxysporum f. sp. fragariae   32  6.2602766 -11.276616 require("LifemapR")  LM <- build_Lifemap(data) # Example with default representation  # one layer lifemap(LM) + lm_markers()  # three different layers  lifemap(LM) + lm_markers() + lm_branches()

title: Use of LifemapR
text: dataset result classification Kraken (Derrick E. Wood, J. Lu, 2019) metagenomic sample coming controlled set 12 known bacterial species (V. Sevim, J. Lee, 2019). First , load data transform LifemapR format. can began visualise data. can example represent number read assigned TaxID color markers following command. Visualisation kraken data representation, markers displayed associated node close enough. possible change way markers displayed display argument. left : display = “requested”, right : display = “leaves” Informations can also displayed user popup label arguments. Usage popup argument Finally, also possible represent data subtree, either size branches color. left : branche’s color, right : branche’s size
code: data(kraken_res)  LM_kraken <- build_Lifemap(df = kraken_res) lifemap(LM_kraken) +    lm_markers(var_fillColor = "coverage_percent", fillColor = "PiYG") # All the nodes that were requested by the user. lifemap(LM_kraken) +    lm_markers(var_fillColor = "coverage_percent", fillColor = "PiYG", display = "requested")  # Only the nodes that have no descendants. lifemap(LM_kraken) +    lm_markers(var_fillColor = "coverage_percent", fillColor = "PiYG", display = "leaves") # When clicking on a node, display the desired information. lifemap(LM_kraken) +    lm_markers(var_fillColor = "coverage_percent", fillColor = "PiYG", popup = "name") # Information on branche's color. lifemap(LM_kraken) +    lm_branches(var_color = "coverage_percent", color = "PiYG")  # Information on branche's size. lifemap(LM_kraken) +    lm_branches(size = "coverage_percent")

code: data(gen_res) LM_gen <- build_Lifemap(df = gen_res) # Visualisation of the Genome size on the fillColor and the TEcontent on the size of markers. lifemap(LM_gen) +    lm_markers(var_fillColor = "Genome_size", fillColor = "PiYG", radius  = "TEcontent_bp", FUN = mean) # Visualisation of the Genome size on the fillColor and the TEcontent on the size of markers. lifemap(LM_gen) +    lm_branches() +   lm_markers(var_fillColor = "Genome_size", fillColor = "PiYG", radius  = "TEcontent_bp", FUN = mean)

what: Dataset of eukaryotes from NCBI database
title: Use of LifemapR
text: dataset contains informations around 1 000 eukaryotes randomly fetched NCBI database. First , load data transform LifemapR format. can began visualise data. Basic visualisation can also choose visualise part data. , can either sort data advance use data argument . Visualisation Plants Finally can visualise discret variables lm_piechats() function following. Visualisation maximum assembly level
code: data(eukaryotes_1000) LM_eukaryotes <- build_Lifemap(df = eukaryotes_1000) # Visualisation of eukaryotes data. lifemap(LM_eukaryotes) +    lm_markers() # Visualisation of Plants. lifemap(LM_eukaryotes) +    lm_markers(data = LM_eukaryotes$df[LM_eukaryotes$df$Group %in% "Plants", ]) # Visualisation of the maximum assembly level. lifemap(LM_eukaryotes) +    lm_piecharts(param = "Group")
